A.2. Tridiagonal of PSP

Given the matrices P and S as follows: The entries (base 0) of S can be expressed as [S]m, n = [2cos (2πm/N) − 4]δ(m − n) + δ(m − n − 1) + δ(m − n + 1). Therefore, PSP is given by [PSP]m, n = [PS]m, :pn as

There are two cases that we should consider: N even or odd. Meanwhile, our target is to prove the tridiagonal of PSP.

  • The non-zero entries in smT are at the indices of 𝒜m = {(m − 1)N, m, (m + 1)N}.

    • Even N: The non-zero entries in pn are at the indices of ℬn = {n} for n = 0, N/2, and of ℬn = {n, N − n} otherwise.

      Investigation of the intersection of 𝒜m and ℬn when |m − n| ≥ 2.

      • n = 0 or n = N/2: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = ⌀.

      • m = 0, N/2: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = ⌀.

      • m < N/2: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = {N − n} ∩ 𝒜m and 𝒜N − m ∩ ℬn = {n} ∩ 𝒜N − m, implying N − n = m − 1 or m or m + 1 such that N/2 ≤ n ≤ N.

        • We simply consider the non-empty intersection case: due to [S]m, kn = [S]N − m, N − kn and [P]kn, n = −[P]N − kn, n.

      • m > N/2: The equations also hold, yielding N − n = m − 1 or m or m + 1 such that 0 ≤ n ≤ N/2.

        • We also solely consider the non-empty intersection case:

          due to [S]m, kn = [S]N − m, N − kn and [P]kn, n = [P]N − kn, n.

    • Odd N: The non-zero entries in pn are at the indices of ℬn = {0} for n = 0 and ℬn = {n, N − n} otherwise.

      Investigation of the intersection of 𝒜m and ℬn when |m − n| ≥ 2.

      • n = 0: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = ⌀.

      • n = ⌊N/2⌋, ⌈N/2⌉: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = ⌀.

      • m ≤ ⌊N/2⌋: 𝒜m ∩ ℬn = {N − n} ∩ 𝒜m and 𝒜N − m ∩ ℬn = {n} ∩ 𝒜N − m, implying N − n = m − 1 or m or m + 1 such that (N + 1)/2 ≤ n ≤ N − 1.[Interval update based on the preceding results]

        • We simply consider the non-empty intersection case:

          due to [S]m, N − kn = [S]N − m, kn and [P]N − kn, n = −[P]kn, n.

      • m ≥ (N + 1)/2: Imply 0 ≤ n ≤ (N − 3)/2.

        • We simply consider the non-empty intersection case: due to [S]m, N − kn = [S]N − m, kn and [P]kn, n = [P]N − kn, n.

From the above analysis [Maybe there is another approach to prove the zero elements but I have no idea so I cope with this by enumerating all possible cases, making it complex], We can assert that all entries beyond the tridiagonal elements are zeros. So PSP is tridiagonal.

The validation of tridiagonal of PSP is given in PSP_validation.m.

Seg03 - Eigenvalue and Eigenvector Decomposition of the Discrete Fourier Transform

Preliminaries

DEF : c(n) = col[c(0), …, c(N − 1)] ∈ ℂN is even iff c(n) = c(−n) and odd iff c(n) = −c(−n) with the definition of c(−n) = col[c(0), c(N − 1), …, c(1)].

Lemma 1 : There exists an orthogonal basis for ℂN consisting of v = [N/2] + 1 even sequences and N − v odd sequences.

  • Proof : An orthogonal basis can be constructed as follows: For N being even, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 2)/2 + 2 = N/2 + 1 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 2)/2 = N/2 − 1.

    For N being odd, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 1)/2 + 1 = (N + 1)/2 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 1)/2.

    Therefore, there are even sequences and ⌈N/2 − 1⌉ = ⌊(N − 1)/2⌋ odd sequences whenever N is odd or even.

Lemma 2 : The eigenvectors of F are either even or odd sequences.

  • Proof : Assume the eigenvector of F is x such that Fx = λx. we have . The orthogonality yields Thus, αi = 0 for λ ∈ {−j, j} and βj = 0 for λ ∈ {−1, 1}. So x is either odd or even.

Theorem 1 : If l is even then Fl ± l is an eigenvector of F with eigenvalue ±1. If l is odd then jFl ∓ l is an eigenvector of F with eigenvalue ±j.

  • Proof : For l being even, F(Fl ± l) = F2l ± Fl = l ± Fl = ±(Fl ± l). For l being odd, F(jFl ∓ l) = −jl ∓ Fl = ±j(jFl ∓ l).
